column1: # Fill one typeII_microstate_fractional_populations.csv template file for all molecules and microstates you have predictions for.
# For each molecule, report as many microstates as your method predicts.
# Add new lines for each predicted microstate.

# e.g. In column 3 report ln(fractional microstate population) at pH 2.10 of your predicted microstate.
# Use scientific notation with 3 decimals of precision (e.g. -2.30e0 or 3.14e-4).

# All major software packages used and their versions.
# Create a new line for each software.
# Level of detail should be at least that used in a publication.
# Please include the values of key parameters, with units, and explain how any statistical uncertainties were estimated.
# Use as many lines of text as you need.
# All text following the "Method:" keyword will be regarded as part of your free text methods description.
Microstate populations for the SAMPL6 pKa molecules were predicted using Epik from the 2017-2 Schrodinger suite.

The SMILES structure provided in the MobleyLab/SAMPL6 github repo was used as input for ligprep. A single, neutral tautomer of the molecule with a 3d structure was generated. This structure was then used as input for Epik calculations.

Epik calculations were used to produce Boltzmann weights for microstates with populations predicted to be > 1% (the default setting). There were converted into log populations through dividing by RT (at 25 Celsius).  Calculations were performed between pH 3.0 and pH 11.0. Microstates not observed were reported as blank.
Epik produced duplicated protonation states for SM16, and which were treated as one state in the output.
Results were processed using the OpenEye toolkits and pandas. Scripts are available at https://github.com/choderalab/SAMPL6-Epik-pKa
